
[1]infamy

   IN'FAMY, n. [L. infamia; in and fama, report.]

   1. Total loss of reputation; public disgrace. Avoid the crimes and
   vices which expose men to infamy.

   2. Qualities which are detested and despised; qualities notoriously bad
   and scandalous; as the infamy of an action.

   3. In law, that loss of character or public disgrace which a convict
   incurs, and by which a person is rendered incapable of being a witness
   or juror.
